[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Proverbs 8:7-10",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Proverbs 8:7-10",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "For my mouth shall speak truth — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Hebrew, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "יהגה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "shall meditate, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "that is, shall speak, not rashly and hastily, but what I have well considered and digested. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Wickedness is an abomination, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — I hate to speak it; therefore you may be assured I shall not deceive you. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "All the words of my mouth — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "All my precepts, promises, threatenings; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "are in righteousness — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Are perfectly just and holy, and conformable to the rules of everlasting righteousness. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "There is nothing froward or perverse, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — Not the least mixture of vanity, or error, or folly in them, as there is in the words of the wisest philosophers. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "They are all plain — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Evident and clear, or right, just, and good; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to him that understandeth — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "To him who, with an honest mind, applies himself to the study of them, in the diligent use of all the means appointed by God to that end: or to him whose mind God hath enlightened by his Spirit, though they seem otherwise to ignorant and carnal men; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to them that find knowledge — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That are truly wise and discerning persons, and taught of God. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Receive my instruction, and not silver — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Rather than silver, that is, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "preferably to silver: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or, the meaning may be, “Give not your heart to money, if you would possess wisdom.” For he seems to intimate the inconsistency of these two studies and designs, and the great hinderance which the love of riches gives to the study of wisdom. Indeed, it is impossible to join these two things together, the love of the world and the love of God, which is here implied in the love of wisdom. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "8:1-11 The will of God is made known by the works of creation, and by the consciences of men, but more clearly by Moses and the prophets. The chief difficulty is to get men to attend to instruction. Yet attention to the words of Christ, will guide the most ignorant into saving knowledge of the truth. Where there is an understanding heart, and willingness to receive the truth in love, wisdom is valued above silver and gold.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Excellent - literally, \"princely things.\" The word is not the same as in marginal reference, and is elsewhere always used of persons (compare \"captain\" in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 9:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 5:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The poetic style of this part of the book applies it here to the things taught, or to the character of the teaching. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "7. For … truth—literally, \"My palate shall meditate,\" or (as Orientals did) \"mutter,\" my thoughts expressed only to myself are truth.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "wickedness—specially falsehood, as opposed to truth.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
